44
00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:30.280
So to begin with,

45
00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:33.660
let's start with the 2D pathology.

46
00:02:33.980 --> 00:02:37.870
Pathology plays a central role in disease diagnosis and

47
00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:41.860
treatment planning across many different disease types and

48
00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:45.920
has proven to be highly effective in clinical practice.

49
00:02:46.340 --> 00:02:50.320
And here is showing a general pipeline of how we do

50
00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:54.260
the conventional 2D pathology. We fix, dehydrate,

51
00:02:54.540 --> 00:02:58.519
embed the tissues, and then section the tissues into thin

52
00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:02.740
sections and stain them with hematoxylin and eosin, and

53
00:03:02.780 --> 00:03:06.720
finally generate the histopathological images for pathologists

54
00:03:06.760 --> 00:03:07.220
to review.

55
00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:11.300
Despite its success, there are a few limitations.

56
00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:15.740
First, it's destructive. As we section the tissues, we

57
00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:19.280
are disrupting the spatial continuity of the depths.

58
00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:23.000
And secondly, it's limited sampling, as we're usually

59
00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:26.740
only analyzing a small number of the sections from the whole

60
00:03:26.760 --> 00:03:30.220
volume. And thirdly, it only provides 2D view.

61
00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:35.640
And for example, for convoluted structure,

62
00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:40.760
some convoluted structures may appear as discrete objects on a

63
00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:43.600
2D plane. And secondly,

64
00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:49.460
in a 2D plane, it's not able to capture

65
00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:53.500
the full spatial organization or heterogeneity across different

66
00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:54.700
tissue regions.

67
00:03:56.240 --> 00:03:59.640
So basically, when we view on 2D, it's an arbitrary

68
00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:03.280
cross-section, and you are missing the information above and below that

69
00:04:03.340 --> 00:04:07.020
section. And finally, the sparse or rare objects may be

70
00:04:07.060 --> 00:04:09.540
entirely missed when we view on a 2D plane.

71
00:04:11.380 --> 00:04:15.280
So to address these limitations, our group has developed this

72
00:04:15.340 --> 00:04:19.200
non-destructive, rapid slide-free 3D

73
00:04:19.380 --> 00:04:21.221
pathology over the past decades.

74
00:04:22.620 --> 00:04:26.600
Similar to the conventional 2D pathology, we fix and stain the tissue,

75
00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:31.020
but instead of sectioning it, we optically clear the tissue

76
00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:33.760
and image them using a 3D microscope.

77
00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:38.940
So this workflow provides three main advantages as it's

78
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:42.650
non-destructive, comprehensive sampling, because we are

79
00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:46.260
capturing essentially 100% of the tissue, and it

80
00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:48.140
provides a 3D view.

81
00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:54.630
And the core technology behind it is called open-top light

82
00:04:54.630 --> 00:04:58.460
sheet microscope. Just to briefly introduce the technology,

83
00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:02.680
OTLS is a 3D microscope platform capable of

84
00:05:02.780 --> 00:05:04.620
imaging large clinical specimen.

85
00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:08.740
And the optical clear tissue will sit on top of this

86
00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:12.760
transparent sample holder, and the light will travel from below

87
00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:15.920
at 45 degree to capture the 3D images.

88
00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:20.450
And here is a video of prostate biopsy imaged

89
00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:21.460
with OTLS.

90
00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:28.700
Given the advantage of our data set, in this study, we are going

91
00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:32.460
to focus on cell interactions. Cell interactions are

92
00:05:33.060 --> 00:05:36.620
increasingly recognized as important contributors to patient

93
00:05:36.680 --> 00:05:38.960
outcomes across many cancer types.

94
00:05:39.520 --> 00:05:43.500
Here are showing two different panels with the same cell

95
00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:47.500
type compositions, and the study finds that the mixing pattern

96
00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:51.220
of different cell types are associated with good

97
00:05:51.280 --> 00:05:55.220
prognosis. So the core idea here is that not

98
00:05:55.260 --> 00:05:58.880
only the cell type composition matters, but also their spatial

99
00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:01.452
organization matters.So

100
00:06:01.552 --> 00:06:04.992
using our 3D dataset, we want to

101
00:06:05.052 --> 00:06:08.512
evaluate whether the 3D cell-cell interactions are

102
00:06:08.552 --> 00:06:10.412
prognostic in prostate cancer.

103
00:06:12.592 --> 00:06:16.091
So graphs are a simple way to model the cell-cell

104
00:06:16.112 --> 00:06:18.772
interactions, where we treat

105
00:06:19.832 --> 00:06:22.492
cells as nodes and interactions as edges.

106
00:06:23.772 --> 00:06:27.092
However, extending this to

107
00:06:27.352 --> 00:06:31.192
3D introduces challenges. We have 10X

108
00:06:31.272 --> 00:06:34.652
more cells and 100 times more interactions,

109
00:06:35.152 --> 00:06:39.092
which lead to two main problems. First, it's computationally

110
00:06:39.172 --> 00:06:42.952
expensive, and second, it has a higher risk for

111
00:06:43.092 --> 00:06:46.972
overfitting, especially when we have limited patient samples.

112
00:06:49.372 --> 00:06:53.312
And looking to biology, we think cells

113
00:06:53.572 --> 00:06:57.272
work collectively to exert meaningful biological functions.

114
00:06:58.052 --> 00:07:01.852
So one potential solution to address the

115
00:07:01.912 --> 00:07:05.812
data skill challenge is to reduce the data size by grouping

116
00:07:05.832 --> 00:07:09.772
cells that are similar. So we

117
00:07:09.812 --> 00:07:13.292
group cells that are phenotypically similar and

118
00:07:13.392 --> 00:07:17.172
spatially adjacent cells into what we call super cells,

119
00:07:17.312 --> 00:07:19.072
and here is the illustration.

120
00:07:22.592 --> 00:07:26.552
Based on this general concept, we developed Skell 3D, a

121
00:07:26.572 --> 00:07:30.192
super cell graph analysis framework for a large 3D

122
00:07:30.212 --> 00:07:31.292
pathology dataset.

123
00:07:32.852 --> 00:07:36.732
For each 3D dataset, we divided them into different

124
00:07:36.792 --> 00:07:40.362
chunks, which allows us to do parallelized

125
00:07:40.432 --> 00:07:40.952
processing.

126
00:07:42.092 --> 00:07:46.072
And for each chunk, we first do nuclei segmentation to

127
00:07:46.132 --> 00:07:49.912
localize the cell, and then we extract the nuclear

128
00:07:49.952 --> 00:07:51.182
morphological features.

129
00:07:52.592 --> 00:07:56.292
And then we form the super cells by grouping spatially

130
00:07:56.332 --> 00:08:00.142
close and morphologically similar cells into super cells, and

131
00:08:00.172 --> 00:08:04.082
each super cell is represented by the main feature of its constituent

132
00:08:04.152 --> 00:08:04.732
nuclei.

133
00:08:06.352 --> 00:08:10.171
And then based on the morphology, the super cell are clustered

134
00:08:10.192 --> 00:08:13.972
into different cell types, and based on that, we form the

135
00:08:14.012 --> 00:08:17.442
super cell graphs. From the graphs, we extract features that

136
00:08:17.472 --> 00:08:20.512
describe the interactions between different subtypes.

137
00:08:23.252 --> 00:08:27.112
And finally, we aggregate the graph-derived feature

138
00:08:27.992 --> 00:08:30.732
into patient-level feature to

139
00:08:33.752 --> 00:08:37.192
evaluate their prognostic performance.

140
00:08:38.913 --> 00:08:42.893
And here is a 3D spatial view of the pipeline.

141
00:08:46.932 --> 00:08:49.152
So we start with the nuclear segmentation,

142
00:08:50.172 --> 00:08:52.152
and then we form the super cells,

143
00:08:53.532 --> 00:08:57.232
and then we do super cell subtyping, and then finally,

144
00:08:57.292 --> 00:08:59.052
we form the super cell graphs.

145
00:09:03.792 --> 00:09:07.472
So to evaluate the prognostic value of Skell

146
00:09:07.692 --> 00:09:11.572
3D, we used a specimen from 76 patients with

147
00:09:11.592 --> 00:09:14.272
known five-year biochemical recurrence outcomes.

148
00:09:14.892 --> 00:09:18.692
Prior studies have shown that nuclear morphology and glandular

149
00:09:18.732 --> 00:09:22.552
morphology are prognostic, which we use as the baseline

150
00:09:22.672 --> 00:09:22.812
here.

151
00:09:23.692 --> 00:09:27.392
And here we show that Skell 3D achieved a higher AUC

152
00:09:27.872 --> 00:09:31.152
for five-year BCR prediction, and similarly

153
00:09:31.272 --> 00:09:34.892
for survival analysis, we also see a similar

154
00:09:34.972 --> 00:09:35.332
trend.

155
00:09:37.892 --> 00:09:41.312
So with the same dataset and evaluation method, we next tested

156
00:09:41.372 --> 00:09:45.152
whether integrating Skell 3D with 3D morphology

157
00:09:45.372 --> 00:09:47.862
further improves the prognostic performance.

158
00:09:48.432 --> 00:09:51.832
So using only 3D morphology achieves an AUC of

159
00:09:51.852 --> 00:09:53.712
0.68, and when

160
00:09:54.072 --> 00:09:57.992
integrating with Skell 3D features,

161
00:09:58.292 --> 00:10:00.112
the AUC increased to 0.8.

162
00:10:01.392 --> 00:10:05.192
And for the survival analysis, we also showed a similar gain,

163
00:10:05.612 --> 00:10:09.112
with the C-index rising from 0.64 to

164
00:10:09.372 --> 00:10:10.092
0.61.

165
00:10:12.332 --> 00:10:16.292
So now we show that the Skell 3D pipeline can extract

166
00:10:16.302 --> 00:10:20.292
prognostic features, but one concern is that compared to the

167
00:10:20.392 --> 00:10:23.792
standard cell level graphs, it may lose its biological

168
00:10:23.852 --> 00:10:26.372
detail and reduce the predictive power.

169
00:10:27.532 --> 00:10:31.472
So to address this, we compared the Skell 3D with a

170
00:10:31.572 --> 00:10:34.932
standard cell level graph and using the identical

171
00:10:35.492 --> 00:10:38.532
downstream evaluation method and processing steps.

172
00:10:40.932 --> 00:10:44.312
We evaluated on two metrics. The first is

173
00:10:44.352 --> 00:10:47.752
performance, was evaluated by the AUC for

174
00:10:47.812 --> 00:10:51.052
five-year BCR prediction. And for

175
00:10:51.092 --> 00:10:54.512
efficiency, was evaluated by computation time.

176
00:10:56.072 --> 00:10:59.772
So on the result, we can see that the super cell achieved a

177
00:10:59.832 --> 00:11:03.111
higher AUC, and in terms of

178
00:11:03.292 --> 00:11:06.872
efficiency, it reduces the computation time by around

179
00:11:07.092 --> 00:11:07.912
25-fold.

180
00:11:09.812 --> 00:11:10.272
So

181
00:11:11.312 --> 00:11:15.252
there are two possible explanations for the increased performance.

182
00:11:15.912 --> 00:11:19.512
One possible explanation is

183
00:11:19.572 --> 00:11:23.332
that by reducing the data complexity, we reduce the risk of

184
00:11:23.412 --> 00:11:26.992
overfitting, especially in the small cohort settings.

185
00:11:27.442 --> 00:11:29.432
And the second hypothesis is that

186
00:11:30.512 --> 00:11:33.912
when we grouping cells into super cells, it may help

187
00:11:34.092 --> 00:11:37.452
reduce the noise from staining

188
00:11:37.512 --> 00:11:41.412
variation, imaging variation, or nuclear segmentation or

189
00:11:41.472 --> 00:11:44.612
feature extraction, which allows us to have a more stable

190
00:11:44.652 --> 00:11:47.832
representation. So to briefly summarize

191
00:11:47.892 --> 00:11:51.072
the whole study is we

192
00:11:51.552 --> 00:11:55.452
propose a super cell level framework for efficiently model cell

193
00:11:55.492 --> 00:11:58.732
interactions in large-scale 3D dataset.

194
00:11:58.752 --> 00:12:02.302
And we show that this approach not only

195
00:12:02.352 --> 00:12:06.172
captures meaningful prognostic information but also

196
00:12:06.892 --> 00:12:10.752
outperforms standard cell level graphs while being

197
00:12:10.792 --> 00:12:14.668
much more computationally efficient.And I would like to

198
